5 STEPS TO PROGRESS YOUR HOLLOW BODY HOLD 💪🏻

This position is a staple for most bodyweight/gymnastics skills. So it is a good one to master.

That said it can be quite difficult to get it right.

It’s important to choose the right progression for you and build from there. This video is from my early days pregnant with Maple. At the moment I am still working towards feeling strong in position numbers 2  and 3. It’s slow progress but it’s worth it not to rush.

Here are 5 levels that will help you progress your hollow hold.

Details:

L1. HOLLOW TUCK:
Zip up through your midline. Keeping lower back glued to the floor and rib caged tucked  in. Try to breathe into space in sides of your belly.
L2. HOLLOW DEADBUGS:
Maintain positioning from level one, whilst alternating each leg to an extended position. 
L3. SEMI HOLLOW HOLD:
Keep legs extended. Squeezing legs together and keeping that tight midline position from level one.
L4. HOLLOW PULL OVERS:
As you extend arms overhead be sure to keep that rib cage tucked and breathe into the space in the sides of your belly. Lower body stays tight.
L5. HOLLOW HOLD:
Imagine you are being pulled in either direction by the hands and feet. Don’t let that lower back lift off the mat or lose that connection with your breath.

Choose the level that works for you and see if you can hold it for 20s then 30, 40 and work your way up to a minute 👌🏻🔥

Do you feel your planks in your shoulder and lower back? 
Try these two tips to help find a stronger, more stable planking position.

1: TUCK YOUR TAIL: 
A slight tuck of the tail will help engage those glutes and abdominals, which will take the load off the low back.
2: LIFT YOUR HEART AWAY FROM THE MAT: Pressing your forearms into the mat and lifting your heart away from the mat will help spread your shoulder blade around your back. This will help out your shoulders in a stronger, more stable position.

I often hear people dismiss planks as too easy but if you try these tips I’m sure you’ll have a new appreciation for this simple movement.

Plus building a strong plank will help provide core stability and endurance for other more challenging bodyweight exercises like push-ups 👌🏻💃🏻

SOUND ON FOR TIPS OR KEEP READING 
I wanted my first pull-up for years when I first started training but it wasn’t till I actually started adding pull-up specific drills to my workouts that I saw results ….. funny that 😝

I literally never trained for pull-ups and somehow expected to be able to do them. Hanging from the bar felt super intimidating to me. So I started with these two simple drills and added them into my other workouts 2 times per week.

MOVE 1: Leg Assisted Pull-ups.
This helps train the vertical pulling movement and build strength where you need it. Your aim is to accumulate between 15-30 reps total in your sets - so in your first session this may be 3 sets of 5 reps. As the weeks progress you can slowly increase this to look more like 3 sets of 10 reps. 
Form tip: think about pulling your elbows to hips rather than getting your chin over the bar. 

Move 2: Passive Hang - eventually progressing to an Active Hang.
Aim to accumulate between 30- 90s of hanging total. This may look like 3 sets of 10s in the beginning but as the weeks progress you can slowly build to 3 sets of 30s and moving to a more Active Hang.
Form tip: wrap that thumb around the bar this will help work on your grip strength.

Save these for your next workout and share with a friend who wants to pull-up with you 💪🏻😝

Breastfeeding on set with @womenshealthaus 

I remember flicking through the pages of Women’s Health in my 20’s dreaming of writing workouts for them one day. 

Fast forward 10 years and here we are. 

In the midst of the postpartum fog - where feeding, burping and settling feels like the sole purpose of your existence, Women’s Health reached out and asked if I could write some workouts for their upcoming issues. 

I couldn’t have been more excited. This was something I could do as me again, a little chance to switch my mum cap back to my PT cap.

Then the mum guilt and anxiety washed over me. What am I going to do with Maple? She is exclusively breastfed I can’t go to the city without her. 

Nervously I reached out the WH team to see if I could bring her along to the shoot and the reply couldn’t have been more comforting and reassuring. 

I’m so grateful for the team for having me and helping keep my little 5 month old entertained while we got the shots done.

I pretty much didn’t miss a week of running from the age of 13 till I fell pregnant the first time at the age of 27…
Running while I was pregnant just didn’t feel that great for me, so I adapted my training to include some lower impact forms of cardio.
I attempted a few times to get back into consistent running postpartum after having Laurie.. but struggled juggling it with my strength training and managing the non optimal recovery conditions involved with child rearing 🫠
Now a year after having my second baby I’m taking a different approach to my return to running. At the moment I’m keeping my runs very short and sweet and not putting any pressure on myself to meet any unrealistic timeframes. Most of my runs are just 1-2 kms with a few short sprints added at the end, that way I can squeeze it in at the end of a strength training session without compromising my rest days.
When I want to cover more distance I opt for run: walk intervals so I can adjust intensity and maintain attention to my form.

I know a lot of you used to follow along on my running journey, so I wanted to give you an update. From someone who used to run 10kms with ease it’s taken quite the mindset adjustment to make such incremental changes but I’ve actually discovered ripping into a shorter, quicker run is a lot of fun 😝

DON’T SKIP THIS PHASE OF YOUR POST PARTUM JOURNEY. 

Take time to rebuild your connection to your core and pelvic floor. Your body has been through a lot over the 9 months you carried your baby and now has a whole new life to adjust to. 

It’s been 12 months of not necessarily “hard” but CONSISTENT work. Slowly progressing my training as my body grew stronger.

This phase feels slow and it can feel like you’re not making any head way but give yourself some grace while you take on this new role. 

I strongly recommend visiting a Women’s Health Physiotherapist or a Pelvic Health Physical Therapist so you can devise a plan to return to training that’s appropriate for you.

3 MOVES YOU CAN TRY AT HOME TO BUILD YOUR PULL-UP STRENGTH 💪

1. ISO Counter Top Hold:
Great for grip strength and building the endurance/ strength in your upper back and accessory muscles for pull-ups.

2. Plank Body Saws:
These are great for training your scapular and core connection which is super useful when performing pull-ups. A strong core will also allow you to keep your body tight when pulling yourself up to the bar which makes it a lot easier 👌

3. Table Rows:
For building upper back strength with the added bonus of training glute and core stability 🙌
